Note: We could EASILY codegen many repetitive functions, but we're not
sacrificing debugging, so they will remain hand written.
The only thing in this codebase we codegen are enums, static data,
and dispatch mechanisms. None of which matter while debugging.

General: All strings converted to u8* over x8*. All code compiles without
warnings.

err.h: Added ERR_FREAD, ERR_LEXBADCHAR, ERR_LEXASSIGN

ascii.h: Readded. It contains the ascii code name, which function
each ascii char should invoke as a lex starter, the label to jump to
( if using computed goto ), and the action to perform after the call
has been made. This can only be JMP or RET, which are just aliases
for continue and return. It is used in both the switch and computer
goto versions of the lexer for expanding switch cases, or generating
the goto labell array. The goto version also expands it's a label list,
including only unique labels. It implements the same as the switch version.

token.c: Contains the basic core token struct. It stores the token
type, its start index in the source code, as its total length. We could use
pointers as a span, but this saves a few bytes. We will be implementing string
interning soon, so we union the .num and .intern fields together. There is only
ever going to be one token, and it is stored directly on the lexer so we don't
have to pass context around. Since our number lexer is custom and doesn't
use strtod(), we store the result into the .num union field directly on the
lexer's token. This file also contains all tokens from the old main.c, which
also is another big list macro that the parser will use heavily for determining
what to do when a token is seen in a particular position. We of course also store
precedence and associativity for proper parse order. x8* TkGetType( TkType ) now
also exists for debugging.

lexer.c: Reimplemented all lex functions from the old main.c. Lex() is now
extremely minimal, only displaying dispatch choice, mechanism, and expansion.

src.c: Removed unused SrcRead( ).